TY  - JOUR
T1  - Banks as Catalysts for Industrialization
AU  - Da Rin, Marco
AU  - Hellmann, Thomas
JO  - Journal of Financial Intermediation
VL  - 11
IS  - 4
SP  - 366
EP  - 397
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/10/01/
SN  - 1042-9573
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1006/jfin.2002.0346
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1042957302903463
AB  - We provide a new theory of the role of banks as catalysts for industrialization. In their influential analysis of continental European industrialization, Gerschenkron and Schumpeter argued that banks promoted the creation of new industries. We formalize this role of banks by introducing financial intermediaries into a “big push” model. We show that banks may act as catalysts for industrialization provided they are sufficiently large to mobilize a critical mass of firms and that they possess sufficient market power to make profits from coordination. The theory provides simple conditions that help explain why banks seem to play a creative role in some but not in other emerging markets. The model also shows that universal banking helps to reduce the cost of acting as catalyst. Journal of Economic Literature Classification Numbers: G21, N2, O14, O16.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Financial Architecture and Economic Performance: International Evidence
AU  - Tadesse, Solomon
JO  - Journal of Financial Intermediation
VL  - 11
IS  - 4
SP  - 429
EP  - 454
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/10/01/
SN  - 1042-9573
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1006/jfin.2002.0352
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1042957302903529
AB  - The paper examines the relation between the architecture of an economy's financial system—its degree of market orientation—and economic performance in the real sector. I find that while market-based systems outperform bank-based systems among countries with developed financial sectors, bank-based systems fare better among countries with underdeveloped financial sectors. Countries dominated by small firms grow faster in bank-based systems and those dominated by larger firms in market-based systems. The findings suggest that recent trends in financial development policies that indiscriminately prescribe market-oriented financial-system architecture to emerging and transition economies might be misguided because suitable financial architecture, in and of itself, could be a source of value. Journal of Economic Literature Classification Numbers: G1, G21, O1, 04.
ER  - 
